ure, it has received relatively little scholarly attention. Bohemia in America, 1858-1920 fills this critical void, discovering and exploring the many textual and geographic spaces in which Bohemia was conjured. Joanna Levin not only provides access to a neglected cultural phenomenon but also to a new and compelling way of charting the development of American literature and culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aAmerican literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aBohemianism in literature. 0aBohemianismzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aBohemianismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aLiterary movementszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aLiterary movementszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804772549zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804772549423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804772549.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles